article.description:
Asjha Jones matched her career high
with 22 points and grabbed eight rebounds to lead the Connecticut
Sun to a 72-65 victory over the San Antonio Silver Stars on Sunday.
article.headline: Sun have enough in reserves to handle Silver Stars
article.linkText: Sun have enough in reserves to handle Silver Stars
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Earlier this month, Connecticut became
the first WNBA team to have all five starters named to the All-Star
team. On Sunday, it was the Sun reserves that got most of the
attention.

Connecticut's backups outscored their counterparts 42-13 with
Asjha Jones leading the way. Jones, the first player off the bench,
matched her career-high with 22 points and had eight rebounds to
lead the Sun to a 72-65 win over the San Antonio Silver Stars.

"Our bench was really, really good," Sun coach Mike Thibault
said. "I cant say enough about them being ready to play and doing
the right things."

With his five starters struggling offensively, Thibault turned
to his subs to pull his Eastern Conference-leading team out of
trouble in the third quarter.

Connecticut (21-6) trailed by as many as seven points in the
first half, before rallying to take a 34-27 lead with the first
score of the third quarter. However, the resurgent Silver Stars
(12-15) jumped ahead 42-40 with 3:16 left in the third.

Jones scored 12 points and LeCoe Willingham had five of her nine
points in a 17-6 run that sealed the win.

"That is why they are a good team," San Antonio coach Dan
Hughes said. "When you are able to bring an Asjha Jones off the
bench, that is saying something. We had a difficult time matching
up with that."

Rookie Sophia Young had 15 points and nine rebounds to lead the
Silver Stars (12-15). Agnieszka Bibrzycka added 13 points, while
four other players scored at least eight points.

The 42-point output was the most points scored from Connecticut
reserves this season. They outscored the starters by 12 points.
Jamie Carey had seven points and four assists, while Laura
Summerton added four points and three rebounds.

"Jamie, LeCoe, Asjha, everyone that went in was awesome. It was
great to see," Sun starting point guard Lindsay Whalen said.
"There are going to be nights when they are going to need to be
ready to play. For whatever reason, the first group really didnt
get into a rhythm tonight so let someone else go in there and try
it out."

Four of the Sun starters -- Whalen, Taj McWilliams-Franklin,
Margo Dydek, and Erin Phillips combined to shoot 5-for-24 (20.8
percent). Katie Douglas, the MVP of the All-Star game on July 12,
was the only other Connecticut player in double figures with 13
points on 5-of-13 shooting.

Whalen, Dydek and Nykesha Sales were selected as All-Star
starters in fan voting, and Douglas was added a reserves by Eastern
Conference coaches. McWilliams-Franklin was selected as a
replacement for Sales, who has been sidelined since July 8 due to
an Achilles' tendon injury.
